## Best Natural Round Diamonds Under $3,500 on Blue Nile

### The Best Value Tier: G-VS2 GIA Excellent

G color in white gold appears near-colorless in normal wear — the round brilliant's light return overwhelms the trace warmth in G at 1ct. VS2 clarity is consistently eye-clean in round brilliants. This combination at GIA Excellent cut is the logical choice at every budget level because every dollar goes into cut quality, not into grade premiums that produce no visible difference.

| Stone | Grade | Price |
|---|---|---|
| [GIA 1ct G-VS2 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090690?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS2 | $3,230 |
| [GIA 1ct G-VS2 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29090694?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS2 | $3,240 |
| [GIA 1ct G-VS2 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112616?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS2 | $3,370 |
| [GIA 1ct G-VS2 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28941971?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS2 | $3,490 |

Four G-VS2 GIA Excellent 1ct rounds, all between $3,230 and $3,490. These are not budget compromises — they are the correct specification target for a 1ct round diamond at any budget level, including unlimited. G-VS2 GIA Excellent is what Farzana recommends to buyers spending $3,000 and to buyers spending $30,000.

The price differences between these stones are proportions: a $3,230 G-VS2 and a $3,490 G-VS2 differ in their crown angle, pavilion angle, or table percentage — the $3,490 stone likely sits closer to the optimal center of GIA's Excellent specification. Always verify table percentage (54–57%), crown angle (34–35°), and pavilion angle (40.6–41.0°) on the GIA certificate before purchasing.

### The One-Grade-Up Option: G-VS1 GIA Excellent

If the budget allows an extra $60–$200 over VS2, G-VS1 provides an additional certainty margin on clarity — particularly useful if the diamond will be set in a halo where the center stone's table is more closely framed.

| Stone | Grade | Price |
|---|---|---|
| [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28915027?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS1 | $3,200 |
| [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28241353?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS1 | $3,260 |
| [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28823788?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS1 | $3,290 |
| [GIA 1ct G-VS1 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26537632?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | G-VS1 | $3,430 |

The G-VS1 stones at $3,200–$3,290 are actually cheaper than some G-VS2 options. This happens because of proportion variation: a G-VS1 stone with slightly less optimal proportions (still GIA Excellent, but at the less favorable end of the specification range) may price below a G-VS2 with superior proportions. This is another reason to read the GIA certificate for each stone individually rather than using grade alone as the price predictor.

